article.headline: Los Angeles improves to 2-0 at home
article.linkText: Mabika, Teasley push Sparks past Sting
article.story:
LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The Los Angeles Sparks turned up the defense
and turned around the game.

Mwaki Mabika scored 19 points and the Sparks rallied in the
second half for an 82-68 victory over the Charlotte Sting on
Wednesday night.

Nikki Teasley added 17 points, six rebounds and six assists for
the Sparks (4-4), who broke a two-game losing streak. Lisa Leslie
scored 16 points and grabbed six rebounds.

"We got after it so much on defense that it helped our
offense," Teasley said. "That's one thing that we've been missing
and have been inconsistent on."

Charlotte Smith-Taylor led the Sting (2-5) with 17 points. Dawn
Staley and Tynesha Lewis added 12 points apiece.

The Sting held a 43-37 lead 24 seconds into the second half when
Los Angeles used a 19-2 surge to move ahead 56-45 with 12:05 to
play. Mabika and DeLisha Milton-Jones each scored five points
during the run, and the Sparks made eight of nine free throws.

"In the first half, we played like the Sting of old," said
Charlotte coach Trudi Lacey. "We controlled the tempo and we got
the shots that we wanted."

Teasley scored 11 points in the second half and Leslie added 10.
Los Angeles made 16 of 25 shots in the half.

Charlotte converted only nine of 25 field goals in the second
half, and scored only two baskets in the final eight minutes in
losing its fourth consecutive game.

"We weren't moving the ball around (in the first half),"
Sparks coach Michael Cooper said. "We got 24 assists and when we
move the ball around, we're a pretty good team."
